					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7898202#post-4148740</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7898202/scp-3732#post-4148740</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sun, 10 Feb 2019 18:21:45 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>This Is War</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2781043</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p><sup>damn yet another super nice and snappy article, lucky me</sup></p> <p>I'll stuff my thoughts and whatnot under a collapsible seeing as others have done so too.</p> <div class="collapsible-block"> <div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;The&nbsp;Good&nbsp;Stuff</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none"> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Begone,&nbsp;thot</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-content"> <p>The overall feeling I've been left with is that this flips the whole 'gone but not forgotten' idiom <em>on its head.</em> And for that alone I like it.</p> <p>It's a brief article but for all that it's composed of it has an incredible level of emotion to it as well - definitely a scenario of 'less is more' that has been pulled off exceptionally well.<br /> I will also add that it is, in its own way, quite unnerving too &#8212; as Nico put it, it's this sense of futility it evokes in that eventually you will be forgotten (and the more I personally think on it, the more unnerving it gets).</p> <p>All in all it feels like a very well-rounded, open-and-close case &#8212; except unlike an open-and-close case there's no sense of closure, and instead I'm left with a mild feeling of existential despair and a need to go hug the dog. <sub><em>I'mma go do that.</em></sub></p> </div> </div> </div> <p>Tl;dr, very much not what I was expecting when I finished reading it, and it did not disappoint.</p> <p>+1, for making me feel things.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
